The NW African fauna, especially that of 
Morocco
, has connection with the fauna of the Iberian Peninsula. This is attributed to the present Strait of 
Gibraltar
forming a bridge of dry land during the Messinian Salinity Crisis (

; 

). The uplift of the northern African and southern Iberian margins, which was probably due to the roll back of the Tethys oceanic lithosphere delaminating bands of lithospheric mantle from beneath the continental margin (

), blocked the passage between the Atlantic and Mediterranean, about 5.96 Mya. This resulted in the regression of the sea, whose water level decreased by more than 
1,000 m
. In place of the Recent Mediterranean there was a desert, crossed by the vast canyons of big rivers, with some water bodies too rich and others too poor in salt, thus making it impossible for marine organisms to inhabit the area. There is a discontinuity in the marine sediments corresponding to that crisis. There were at least ten sea transgressions in the Mediterranean during the Messinian (

). Instead of the sea there were numerous brackish water ‘‘LagoMare’’ basins, big and deep, though brackish, habitats. Later, 5.33 Mya, the Pliocene transgression delimited the Miocene, initiating the Pliocene. There was an abrupt catastrophic transgression of water from the Atlantic, probably caused by gravity-induced slumping from the western margin of the 
Gibraltar
arch into the Atlantic abyssal plains (

).

The shells were photographed with a Canon EOS 50D digital camera, under a Nikon SMZ18 microscope with a dark field. The dissections were done under a Nikon SMZ18 microscope with a dark field. Morphometric parameters of the shell were measured by one person using a Nikon DS-5 digital camera and ImageJ image analysis software (

). The linear measurements were logarithmically transformed. Principal component analysis (PCA) based on the correlation matrix was calculated, applying a descriptive, non-stochastic approach. The original observations were projected into PC space to show morphological similarity relationships between the specimens without any a priori classification. For PCA, the Clust Vis 2.0 web tool (

) was used. The penes were photographed under Motic microscope with a dark field. Morphological terminology follows 

.

In the phylogenetic analysis, sequences from GenBank were used (
Table 3
). The sequences were selected on the basis of Barcode of Life Data System (

). All sequences were initially aligned in MUSCLE (

) implemented in MEGA 7 (

) and then checked in Bioedit 7.1.3.0 (

). Genetic distances were calculated in MEGA 7. The estimation of the proportion of invariant sites and the saturation tests for entire data sets (

, 

) were performed with DAMBE (

). The data were analysed using approaches based on Bayesian inference (BI) and maximum likelihood (ML). For RAxML analysis, the jModelTest2 via the CIPRES Science Gateway (

) was used to find the best-fitting model, the model HKY+G+I was chosen. The ML analysis was conducted in RAxML-NG v. 0.8.0 (

) via web service available at https://raxml-ng.vital-it.ch/, with ten random and ten parsimony starting trees. In the BI analysis, the K81+G+I model of nucleotide substitution was applied in the tree reconstruction. Model was selected using MrModelTest 2.4 (

). The analyses were run using MRBAYES v. 3.2.7a (

) with defaults of most priors. Two simultaneous analyses were performed, each with 10,000,000 generations, with one cold chain and three heated chains, starting from random trees and sampling the trees every 1,000 generations. The first 25% of the trees were discarded as burn-in. The analyses were summarized as a 50% majority-rule consensus tree. Convergence was checked in TRACER v.1.7.1 (

), in all cases Effective Sample Size exceeded 200. FigTree v. 1.4.4 (

) was used to visualize the trees. Three species delimitation methods were performed: Poisson Tree Processes (PTP) (

), Automatic Barcode Gap Discovery (ABGD) (

) and Assemble Species by Automatic Partitioning (ASAP) (

). The PTP approach was run using the web server https://species.h-its.org/ptp/, with 100,000 MCMC generations, 100 thinning and 0.1 burn-in. We used the RAXML output phylogenetic tree. The ABGD approach used the web server (https://bioinfo.mnhn.fr/abi/public/abgd/abgdweb.html) with the default parameters. The ASAP approach was run using the web server (https://bioinfo.mnhn.fr/abi/public/asap/) according to simple distance (p-distances). The Fastachar application (

) and DeSignate (

) were used to distinguish particular species from another species, by determining the Molecular Diagnostic Characters (MDCs) for COI. 
Two types
of characters were accepted: at binary positions (the character states in the query group are different from uniform character states in the reference group) and at asymmetric positions (the character states in the query group are different from not uniform character states in the reference group).

